00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:47.160
So, last week we saw how commercial farming transformed the American west and gave us mythical cowboys and unfortunately not-so-mythical
Indian reservations.

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:53.440
Today we leave the sticks and head for the
cities, as so many Americans and immigrants
have done throughout this nation’s history.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:57.320
I mean we may like to imagine that the history of America is all “Go west young man,”

00:00:57.320 --> 00:01:01.720
but in fact from Mark Twain to pretty much
every hipster in Brooklyn, it’s the opposite.

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:04.720
So, population was growing everywhere
in America after 1850.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:08.860
Following a major economic downturn in
the 1890s, farm prices made a comeback,

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:14.320
and that drew more and more people out
west to take part in what would eventually be
called agriculture’s golden age.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:20.300
Although to be fair agriculture’s real golden age was
in like 3000 BCE when Mesopotamians were like,

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:24.640
“Dude, if we planted these in rows, we
could have MORE OF IT THAN WE CAN EAT.”

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:26.360
So it was really more of a second golden age.

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:30.340
But anyway, more than a million land claims
were filed under the Homestead Act in the 1890s.

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:37.660
And between 1900 and 1910 the
populations of Texas and Oklahoma together
increased by almost 2 million people.

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:41.560
And another 800,000 moved into Kansas,
the Dakotas, and Nebraska. That’s right.

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:45.420
People moved TO Nebraska.
Sorry, I just hadn’t yet offended Nebraskans.

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:47.840
I’m looking to get through the list before
the end of the year.

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:55.680
But one of the central reasons that so many people
moved out west was that the demand for agricultural
products was increasing due to...the growth of cities.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:02.400
In 1880, 20% of the American population
lived in cities and there were 12 cities with a
population over 100,000 people.

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:07.860
This rose to 18 cities in 1900 with the
percentage of urban dwellers rising to 38%.

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:13.560
And by 1920, 68% of Americans lived in cities 
and 26 cities had a population over 100,000.

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:22.880
So in the 40 years around the turn of the 20th century,
America became the world’s largest industrial power
and went from being predominantly rural to largely urban.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:26.400
This is, to use a technical historian term,
a really big deal.

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:29.460
Because it didn’t just make cities possible,
but also their products.

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:35.560
It’s no coincidence that while all this was
happening, we were getting cool stuff like
electric lights and moving picture cameras.

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:37.520
Neither of which were invented by
Thomas Edison.

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:41.600
I don’t know if you’ve noticed, but suddenly there are a lot more photographs in Crash Course U.S. History b-roll.

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:44.560
So the city leading the way in this urban
growth was New York,

00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:50.420
especially after Manhattan was
consolidated with Brooklyn (and the Bronx,
Queens and Staten Island) in 1898.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:56.320
At the turn of the century, the population of the 23
square miles of Manhattan Island was over 2 million.

00:02:56.320 --> 00:02:59.300
And the combined 5 boroughs had a
population over 4 million.

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:05.360
But, while New York gets most of the attention
in this time period, and all time periods since, it
wasn’t alone in experiencing massive growth.

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:12.420
Like, my old hometown of Chicago, after
basically burning to the ground in 1871, became
the second largest city in America by the 1890s.

00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:15.700
Also, they reversed the flow of the
freaking Chicago River.

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:18.820
Probably the second most impressive
feat in Chicago at the time.

00:03:18.820 --> 00:03:21.920
The first being that the Cubs won two
World Series.

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:27.580
Even though I’m sorely tempted to chalk up the
growth of these metropolises to a combination of
better nutrition and a rise in skoodilypooping,

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:36.440
I’m going to have to bow to stupid historical accuracy and tell you that much of the growth had to do with the phenomenon that this period is most known for: immigration.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:40.680
Of course, by the end of the 19th century, immigration
was not a new phenomenon in the United States.

00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:45.580
After the first wave of colonization by English people, and Spanish people, and other Europeans,

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.900
there was a new wave of Scandinavians, French people, and especially the Irish.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:55.700
Most of you probably know about the
potato famine of the 1840s that led a million
Irish men and women to flee.

00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:57.840
If you don’t know
about it, it was awful.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:05.040
And the second largest wave of immigrants was
made up of German speakers, including a number of
liberals who left after the abortive revolutions of 1848.

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:06.640
All right, let’s go to the Thought Bubble.

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:13.320
The Irish had primarily been farmers in the
motherland, but in America, they tended to
stay in cities, like New York and Boston.

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:20.420
Most of the men began their working lives as
low-wage unskilled laborers, but over time they came
to have much more varied job opportunities.

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:26.380
Irish immigrant women worked too, some in
factories or as domestic servants in the homes
of the growing upper class.

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:33.240
Many women actually preferred the freedom that
factory labor provided and one Irish factory woman
compared her life to that of a servant by saying:

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:39.140
“Our day is ten hours long, but when it’s
done, it’s done, and we can do what we like
with the evenings.

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:42.160
That’s what I’ve heard from every nice girl
that’s tried service.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:46.000
You’re never sure that your soul is your
own except when you’re out of the house.”

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.840
Most German speakers had been farmers in their
home countries and would remain farmers in the US,
but a number of skilled artisans also came.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:55.660
They tended to stay in cities and
make a go of entrepreneurship.

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:59.200
Bismarck himself saw emigration from
Germany as a good thing saying,

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:02.020
“The better it goes for us, the higher the
volume of emigration.”

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:04.720
And that’s why we named a city in
North Dakota after him.

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:11.060
Although enough German immigrants came to New York that the lower east side of Manhattan came to be known for a time as Kleindeutschland (little Germany),

00:05:11.060 --> 00:05:15.280
many moved to the growing cities of the
Midwest like Cincinnati and St. Louis.

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:17.940
Some of the most famous German
immigrants became brewers.

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:24.280
And America is much richer for the arrival of men like Frederick Pabst, Joseph Schlitz, and Adolphus Busch.

00:05:24.280 --> 00:05:26.020
And by richer, I mean drunker.

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.420
Hey. Thanks for not ending on a downer,
Thought Bubble.

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:29.840
I mean, unless you count alcoholism.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:40.020
So, but by the 1890s, over half of the 3.5 million immigrants who came to our shores came from southern and eastern Europe, in particular Italy and the Russian and Austro Hungarian empires.

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:42.960
They were more likely than previous
immigrants to be Jewish or Catholic,

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:48.420
and while almost all of them were looking
for work, many were also escaping political
or religious persecution.

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.920
And by the 1890s they also had to face
new “scientific” theories,

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:56.080
which I’m putting in air quotes to be clear because
there was nothing scientific about them,

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:04.620
which consigned them to different “races” whose
low level of civilization was fit only for certain kinds of 
work and predisposed them to criminality.

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:12.540
The Immigration Restriction League was founded
in Boston in 1894 and lobbied for national legislation
that would limit the numbers of immigrants,

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:18.060
and one such law even passed Congress in 1897
only to be vetoed by President Grover Cleveland.

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:22.120
Good work, Grover! You know, his first name
was Stephen, but he called himself Grover.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:23.700
I would have made a different choice.

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:25.960
But before you get too excited about
Grover Cleveland,

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:31.060
Congress and the President were able to agree on
one group of immigrants to discriminate against:
the Chinese.

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:38.980
Chinese immigrants, overwhelmingly male, had been coming to the United States, mostly to the West, since the 1850s to work in mines and on the railroads.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:45.320
They were viewed with suspicion because they looked different, spoke a different language, and they had “strange” habits, like regular bathing.

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:54.520
By the time the Chinese Exclusion Act went into effect in 1882, there were 105,000 people of Chinese descent living in the United States, mainly in cities on the West Coast.

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:59.940
San Francisco refused to educate Asians until the state Supreme Court ordered them to do so.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:03.260
And even then the city responded by
setting up segregated schools.

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:05.360
The immigrants fought back through
the courts.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:13.920
In 1886, in the case of Yick Wo v. Hopkins the United States Supreme court ordered San Francisco to grant Chinese-operated laundries licenses to operate.

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:16.940
Then in 1898 in United States v. Wong Kim Ark,

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:24.560
the Court ruled that American born children of Chinese immigrants were entitled to citizenship under the 14th Amendment, which should have been a duh but wasn’t.

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:29.140
We’ve been hard on the Supreme Court here at
Crash Course, but those were two good decisions.

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:30.560
You go, Supreme Court!

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:38.840
But despite these victories Asian immigrants continued to face discrimination in the form of vigilante-led riots like the one in Rock Springs, Wyoming that killed 26 people.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:43.820
And congressionally approved restrictions, many of which the Supreme Court did uphold, so, meh.

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:49.820
Also it’s important to remember that this
large-scale immigration – and the fear of it –
was part of a global phenomenon.

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:56.560
At its peak between 1901 and the outbreak
of World War 1 in 1914, 13 million immigrants
came to the United States.

00:07:56.560 --> 00:08:03.740
In the entire period touched off by the
industrialization from 1840 until 1914, a total
of 40 million people came to the U.S.

00:08:03.740 --> 00:08:11.860
But at least 20 million people emigrated to other
parts of the Western Hemisphere, including Brazil,
the Caribbean, Canada (yes, Canada) and Argentina.

00:08:11.860 --> 00:08:16.220
As much as we have Italian immigrants to thank
for things like pizza (and we do thank you),

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:20.240
Argentina can be just as grateful for the
immigrant ancestors of Leo Messi.

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:22.800
Also the Pope, although he has never once
won La Liga.

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:27.160
And there was also extensive immigration
from India to other parts of the British Empire
like South Africa;

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:31.600
Chinese immigration to South America and
the Caribbean; I mean, the list goes on and on.

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:34.820
In short, America is
not as special as it fancies itself.

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:40.040
