00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:30.880
Mary Antin? Does she even have
a Wikipedia page?!

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:35.500
She does? Did you write it, Stan? Stan
wrote her Wikipedia page. AH.

00:09:35.500 --> 00:09:38.820
So, this document, while it was written by
someone who should not have a Wikipedia page,

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:43.860
points out that most immigrants to America were
coming for the most obvious reason: opportunity.

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:48.080
Industrialization, both in manufacturing and
agriculture, meant that there were jobs in America.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:54.100
There was so much work, in fact, that
companies used labor recruiters who went
to Europe to advertise opportunities.

00:09:54.100 --> 00:09:57.960
Plus, the passage was relatively cheap, provided
you were only going to make it once in your life,

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:01.820
and it was fast, taking only 8 to 12
days on the new steam powered ships.

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:05.960
The Lower East Side of Manhattan became the
magnet for waves of immigrants, first Germans,

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:12.640
then Eastern European Jews and Italians, who
tended to re-create towns and neighborhoods
within blocks and sometimes single buildings.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:18.760
Tenements, these 4, 5 and 6 story buildings
that were designed to be apartments, sprang
up in the second half of the 19th century

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:25.180
and the earliest ones were so unsanitary
and crowded that the city passed laws requiring
a minimum of light and ventilation.

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:32.320
And often these tenement apartments doubled as workspaces because many immigrant women  and children took in piecework, especially in the garment industry.

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:39.940
Despite laws mandating the occasional window
and outlawing the presence of cows on public streets,
conditions in these cities were pretty bad.

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:47.880
Things got better with the construction of
elevated railroads and later subways that 
helped relieve traffic congestion but they
created a new problem: pickpockets.

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:51.580
“Pickpockets take advantage of the confusion
to ply their vocation…

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:54.720
The foul, close, heated air is poisonous.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:58.560
A healthy person cannot ride a dozen
blocks without a headache.”

00:10:58.560 --> 00:10:59.800
So that’s changed!

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:04.860
This new transportation technology also enabled
a greater degree of residential segregation in cities.

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:09.980
Manhattan’s downtown area had, at one time,
housed the very rich as well as the very poor,

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:14.880
but improved transportation meant that people
no longer had to live and work in the same place.

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:22.160
The wealthiest, like Cornelius Vanderbilt and J.P. Morgan, constructed lavish palaces for themselves and uptown townhouses were common.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:29.880
But until then, one of the most notable feature of
gilded age cities like New York was that the rich and
the poor lived in such close proximity to each other.

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:37.340
And this meant that with America’s growing
urbanization, the growing distance between rich
and poor was visible to both rich and poor.

00:11:37.340 --> 00:11:43.560
And much as we see in today’s megacity, this
inability to look away from poverty and economic
inequality became a source of concern.

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:48.040
Now one way to alleviate concern is to create
suburbs so you don’t have to look at poor people,

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:53.660
but another response to urban problems
was politics, which in cities like New York, 
became something of a contact sport.

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:56.280
Another response was the so-called
progressive reform movement.

00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:59.300
And in all these responses and in the
issues that prompted them –

00:11:59.300 --> 00:12:07.940
urbanization, mechanization, capitalism, the
distribution of resources throughout the social order –
we can see modern industrial America taking shape.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:12.560
And that is the America we live in today.
